revision.text:
{{Otheruses|[[Archaeology]] terminology for overburden|Other uses|覆土}}
'''Fukudo''' (覆土, Overburden) refers to the [[soil]] (or [[strata]]) deposited within [[features]] in the context of [[archaeology]]. It is also called {{ill|Emido|ja|埋土}} (うめど・うめつち・まいど)<ref>In [[archaeology]] and [[excavation]] contexts, "overburden" and "buried soil" are often used synonymously to refer to the soil accumulated within features. For example, in the reference text 'A Guide to Excavation Surveys,' the term is presented as "buried soil (overburden)" (p. 94).</ref>.

== Overview ==
Overburden may contain information about the feature, or it may consist of soil that merely flowed into the feature. The deposition can provide clues about the nature of the feature and the process of its abandonment. Generally, overburden helps to reveal whether a feature was abandoned gradually and how, such as whether the ceiling of a [[pit structure]] or [[kiln]] collapsed, as determined through [[excavation surveys]]. Observations are often made using section belts (soil layer belts), which preserve strips of overburden for analysis. This allows researchers to study the [[cross-sectional diagrams (archaeology)|stratigraphy]] and infer the processes of burial and abandonment{{Sfn|Agency for Cultural Affairs|2010|pp=93-116}}<ref>Such stratigraphic observations, recorded in cross-sectional diagrams, are referred to as section drawings.</ref>.

In cases where overburden contains unique information about a feature, for instance, the remains of burned wood from a fire-destroyed [[pit dwelling]], it may reveal details such as the materials used in construction (e.g., earth or thatch for roofs) or even the sequence of events during the collapse. Such wooden remains can provide data on the types of trees used, their structural arrangement, and, if fortunate, samples suitable for [[dendrochronology]] or [[radiocarbon dating]]. Additionally, microfossils such as [[diatoms]] or [[pollen]] may provide insights into the environmental conditions of the time.

At the [[Fukiage Shell Mound]] in [[Wako, Saitama|Wako City]], [[Saitama Prefecture]], a pit dwelling was found buried under a [[shell layer]], with nearly intact pottery discovered beneath. Observations of the underlying strata, devoid of artifacts down to the dwelling floor, provided evidence of a cyclical human behavior pattern involving the site's use, abandonment, and subsequent transformation into a disposal site for pottery and later shells. This cyclical pattern, known as the "Fukiage Pattern," was identified through overburden analysis and proposed by {{ill|Tatsuo Kobayashi|ja|小林達雄}}.

