'''Overburden''' (覆土, Fukudo) refers to the {{ill|soil|ja|土壌}} (or {{ill|stratigraphic layers|ja|土層 (考古学)}}) that accumulates within {{ill|archaeological features|ja|遺構}}. It is also referred to as "buried soil" (埋土, umedo, umetsuchi, or maido)<ref>In {{ill|archaeology|ja|考古学}} and {{ill|excavation|ja|発掘調査}}, the terms "overburden" and "buried soil" are often used synonymously to describe sediment within features. For instance, in the reference book "Handbook of Excavation Surveys," both are described together as "buried soil (overburden)" (p. 94).</ref>.

== Overview ==
Overburden sometimes contains information related to the archaeological feature, while at other times, it merely represents soil that has flowed into the feature. It can reveal information about the feature’s characteristics and its process of abandonment. For example, overburden can indicate whether a feature was abandoned gradually or how it was filled. For features such as {{ill|subterranean pits|ja|地下式坑}} or {{ill|kilns|ja|窯}} remains, excavation can uncover whether the roof collapsed during abandonment. Typically, overburden is examined using sectional belts (stratigraphic belts) that leave strips of soil intact for observation, allowing researchers to infer the feature's burial and abandonment processes through {{ill|stratigraphic observation|ja|実測図 (考古学)}}{{Sfn|Agency for Cultural Affairs|2010|pp=93-116}}<ref>Cross-sections illustrating overburden deposition are referred to as sectional diagrams.</ref>.

When overburden contains specific information about a feature, such as evidence of a fire that destroyed a {{ill|pit dwelling|ja|竪穴建物}} or materials discarded during abandonment, it can provide valuable insights. For instance, if wood from a collapsed structure is preserved in the overburden, it can indicate the materials used in the roof or walls, and even the sequence of collapse. Such materials may also serve as samples for {{ill|dendrochronology|ja|年輪年代学}} or {{ill|radiocarbon dating|ja|放射性炭素年代測定}}. Furthermore, microfossils such as {{ill|diatoms|ja|珪藻}} or {{ill|pollen|ja|花粉}} within the overburden can provide clues about the surrounding environment at the time.

At the {{ill|Fukiage Shell Midden|ja|吹上貝塚}} in {{ill|Wako, Saitama|ja|和光市}}, a pit dwelling was found buried under layers of shell midden, with nearly intact pottery discovered beneath the shells. Below this, a sterile layer free of artifacts was identified as overburden covering the floor of the dwelling. Observations of these layers suggested a pattern of human behavior where the site transitioned from a dwelling to a refuse area for pottery and later for shells. This cyclical pattern, known as the "Fukiage Pattern," was proposed by {{ill|Tatsuo Kobayashi|ja|小林達雄}} based on overburden analysis.

