'''Overburden Fukudo''' (覆土) refers to layers of [[soil]] ({{ill|stratigraphy|ja|土層 (考古学)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/stratigraphy|qq=}}) that accumulate within a {{ill|Feature (archaeology)|lt=feature|ja|遺構|1=Feature_(archaeology)|lt=Archaeological Feature|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Feature (archaeology)|13=User:Immanuelle/Feature_(archaeology)|qq=}} in [[archaeology]].<ref>[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0305440321000996 The archaeology of overburden: Method within the madness at Švédův Stůl, Czech Republic - ScienceDirect]</ref><ref name=":0" /> It is also referred to as {{ill|Umedo|ja|埋土|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Umedo|qq=}} (うめど・うめつち・まいど).<ref name=":0">In [[archaeology]] and excavation work, the terms "覆土" (Fukudo) and "埋土" (Umedo) are nearly synonymous when describing accumulated soil within structures. For example, the reference guide "発掘調査のてびき" uses the term "埋土（覆土）" (Umedo/Fukudo) (p. 94).</ref>

== Overview ==

Fukudo can contain information about the structure or simply consist of soil that flowed into the area. It provides insights into the characteristics of the structure and its abandonment process. For instance, it may reveal whether the structure's abandonment occurred gradually or abruptly, and whether features like {{ill|subterranean pits|ja|地下式坑|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/subterranean pits|qq=}} or {{ill|kiln|lt=kiln ruins|ja|窯|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/kiln|qq=}} collapsed. Through {{ill|archaeological excavation|ja|発掘調査|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/archaeological excavation|qq=}}, researchers often leave section belts (stratigraphic belts) to observe the soil layers, allowing them to infer the burial and abandonment processes of the structure.{{Sfn|Agency for Cultural Affairs|2010|pp=93-116}}<ref>Such stratigraphic observations are expressed as cross-sectional diagrams known as section drawings.</ref>

When Fukudo contains unique information about a structure, such as remnants of {{ill|burned wood|ja|焼け落ちた木材|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/burned wood|qq=}}, it can indicate whether the building was destroyed by fire or abandoned. In favorable conditions, researchers can determine materials used in the roof (e.g., soil, thatch), the sequence of destruction, and the types of wood used in its construction. The material may also serve as samples for {{ill|tree-ring dating|ja|年輪年代学|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/tree-ring dating|qq=}} and {{ill|radiocarbon dating|ja|放射性炭素年代測定|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/radiocarbon dating|qq=}}. Furthermore, microfossils such as {{ill|diatoms|ja|珪藻|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/diatoms|qq=}} and {{ill|pollen|ja|花粉|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/pollen|qq=}} may provide insights into the environment at the time.

At the {{ill|Fukiage Shell Mound|ja|吹上貝塚|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fukiage Shell Mound|qq=}} in {{ill|Wako City|ja|和光市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wako City|qq=}}, {{ill|Saitama Prefecture|ja|埼玉県|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saitama Prefecture|qq=}}, pit dwellings buried under shell layers yielded near-complete pottery. Beneath these layers, undisturbed soil was observed as Fukudo, showing that the site transitioned from a dwelling to a disposal site for pottery and later for shells. This cycle of human activity was identified as the "Fukiage Pattern" by {{ill|Tatsuo Kobayashi|ja|小林達雄|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tatsuo Kobayashi|qq=}}, based on observations of Fukudo.

